    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        The volume of a pyramid is one-third the area of its base multiplied by its height. 
        This means that if you know the area of the base and the height, you can easily find the volume.
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore, the volume of each pyramid
        is given by;
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Volume}= \frac{1}{3}(\text{Base Area(A)} \times \text{Height(h)})</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Which can be written as;
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Volume}= \frac{1}{3}(\text{A} \times \text{h})</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Where, where <m>\textbf{A}</m> is the area of the base and <m>\textbf{h}</m> the
       perpendicular height of the pyramid
    </p>


    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the volume of te figure below.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="Volume-of-pyramid-example">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Base rectangle (6 cm length along x-axis, 4 cm width along y-axis)
                    \draw[very thick,fill=cyan] (0,0) -- (6,0) -- (6,4) -- (0,4) -- cycle;



                    % Sides to apex
                    \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (3,6);
                    \draw[very thick] (6,0) -- (3,6);
                    \draw[very thick] (6,4) -- (3,6);
                    \draw[very thick] (0,4) -- (3,6);

                    % Dashed height from base centre to apex
                    \draw[very thick,dashed] (3,2) -- (3,6);

                    % Label the height
                    \node[right] at (3,3) {8 cm};

                    % Label base dimensions
                    % Length (6 cm)

                    \node at (3,-0.5) {6 cm};

                    % Width (4 cm)

                    \node[rotate=90] at (-1,2) {4 cm};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the volume of the pyramid, we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} \amp \text{Base Area} \amp \text{Height} </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The base area is a rectangle with length <m>6 \, \text{cm}</m> and width <m>4 \, \text{cm}</m>, so:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Base area } =\amp  6 \, \text{cm} \times 4 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 24 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} = \frac{1}{3}(\text{Base Area} \times \text{Height})</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3}(24 \, \text{cm}^2 \times 8 \, \text{cm}) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3}(192 \, \text{cm}^3) </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 64 \, \text{cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of the pyramid is <m>{\color{blue}64 \, \text{cm}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate the volume of the following pyramids:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a) ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Triangular based with equal sides each measuring <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m> and a height of <m>30\, \text{cm}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            (Give your answer to <m>2</m> decimal places)
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Square based of sides <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m> and a height of <m>25\, \text{cm}</m>.
                        </p>
                        
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rectangular based of sides <m>12 \, \text{cm}</m> and <m>16 \, \text{cm}</m> and slant edge <m>26\, \text{m}</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a) ">
                    <li >
                        <p>
                            Triangular based pyramid
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since the base is triangular, we first find the area of the base.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Base of the triangle}= \amp \sqrt{10^2 - 5^2}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \sqrt{100 - 25}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \sqrt{75}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp 5\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \approx =\amp 8.66 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The area of the base triangle is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} = \amp  \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Base} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 8.66 \times 10 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 43.30 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The volume of the pyramid is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Volume} = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 43.30 \times 30 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 433.00 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>

                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Square based pyramid
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since the base is square, we first find the area of the base.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Area} = \amp \text{Side}^2 = 12^2 = 144 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The volume of the pyramid is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Base Area} = \amp 12^2 = 144 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 144 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Volume} = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 144 \times 25 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1200.00 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>

                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rectangular-based pyramid
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Base sides: <m>12 \, \text{m} \, \text{by} \, 16 \, \text{m}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Slant edge <m> = 26 \, \text{m}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Find height using Pythagoras theorem that is  find half of base diagonal:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{d} =\amp \sqrt{(12^2 + 16^2)}  </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{(144 + 256)}  </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{400}  </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 20 \, \text{m}  </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Use slant edge (<m>
                            26 \, \text{m}</m>) as hypotenuse to find height:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{h} =\amp \sqrt{(26^2 - 10^2)} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{(676 - 100)} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{576} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 24 \, \text{m} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The base area is gotten by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Base Area} = \amp \text{Length} \times \text{Width} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 12 \, \text{m} \times 16 \, \text{m} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 192 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The volume of the pyramid is given by:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{Volume} = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 192 \times 24 \, \text{m}^3</mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 1536.00 \, \text{m}^3</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volumes of the pyramids are:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a) ">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Triangular based pyramid: <m>{\color{blue}433.00 \, \text{cm}^3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Square based pyramid: <m>{\color{blue}1200.00 \, \text{cm}^3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rectangular based pyramid: <m>{\color{blue}1536.00 \, \text{m}^3}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A crystal is in the form of two similar square based pyramids joined at their bases as shown below. Calculate the volume 
                of the crystal if the height of the whole crystal.
            </p>
            <image source="/Chrystal.png" width="80%">
                <shortdescription>Diagram of the crystal structure</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The volume of a pyramid is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The base area of a square pyramid is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Base Area} = \amp \text{Side}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 8^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 64 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of the crystal pyramid is given by:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{3} \times 64 \, \text{cm}^2 \times 12 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{768}{3} \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 256.00 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of the crystal is <m>{\color{blue}256 \, \text{cm}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    
